05255nam a22007815i 9780231537452DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013044356  a(OCoLC)979953856  a97802315374527 a10.7312/suga167182doi  a(DE-B1597)458521  a(OCoLC)881610975  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL789.S8bZ4713 2014 4aPL789.S8bZ4713 2015 7aLIT0080302bisacsh04a741.59732231 aSugawara no Takasue no Musume, Sugawara no Takasue no Musume, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Sarashina Diary :bA Woman's Life in Eleventh-Century Japan /cSugawara no Takasue no Musume Sugawara no Takasue no Musume. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b‹B›17 illus., 3 maps‹/B›  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTranslations from the Asian Classics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: A Collaborative Project -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on the Translation and Technical Matters -- tIntroduction and Study -- t1. Text and Author -- t2. The Relationship of Theme and Structure -- t3. Dreams and Religious Consciousness -- t4. A Child’s Viewpoint and Layers of Narration -- t5. Text and Intertext: The Sarashina Diary and the Tale of Genji -- t6. A Life Composed in Counterpoint -- tSarashina Diary -- tAfterword -- tAppendix 1. Family and Social Connections -- tAppendix 2. Maps -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA thousand years ago, a young Japanese girl embarked on a journey from the wild East Country to the capital. She began a diary that she would continue to write for the next forty years and compile later in life, bringing lasting prestige to her family. Some aspects of the author's life and text seem curiously modern. She married at age thirty-three and identified herself as a reader and writer more than as a wife and mother. Enthralled by romantic fiction, she wrote extensively about the disillusioning blows that reality can deal to fantasy. The Sarashina Diary is a portrait of the writer as reader and an exploration of the power of reading to shape one's expectations and aspirations. As a person and an author, this writer presages the medieval era in Japan with her deep concern for Buddhist belief and practice. Her narrative's main thread follows a trajectory from youthful infatuation with romantic fantasy to the disillusionment of age and concern for the afterlife; yet, at the same time, many passages erase the dichotomy between literary illusion and spiritual truth. This new translation captures the lyrical richness of the original text while revealing its subtle structure and ironic meaning. The introduction highlights the poetry in the Sarashina Diary and the juxtaposition of poetic passages and narrative prose, which brings meta-meanings into play. The translators' commentary offers insight into the author's family and world, as well as the fascinating textual legacy of her work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAuthors, JapaneseyHeian period, 794-1185vDiaries. 0aWomenzJapanxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh1 aArntzen, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArntzen, Sonja.1 aItō, Moriyuki.1 aMoriyuki, Itō, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/suga1671840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97802315